US is the largest farm product exporter country, China is the largest farm product producer. The conclusion is obvious. We have a food shortage crisis on our hands ready to explode in winter and 2023, while inflation still needs to be tamed. 11/

incl. large swaths of France, Germany, and Eastern Europe, esp. Ukraine, Slovakia, Moldova, all big agriculture producers and exporters. Oh, and we haven't started talking about the #drought in US yet. 10/
Food crisis: agriculture is hit by the quad whammy of no water, pricey energy, fertilizer shortage, and high heat. Soil moisture and precipitation levels are drier than normal for most of Europe 9/

That's why European electricity prices are soaring. Year-ahead contract for both German and French electricity hit ~1,000 euros per MWH (megawatt hour). Nitty-gritty of power pricing aside, this broadly damages Europe's industrial output & residential use 8/

But ships had to reduce their capacity to as low as ~25% b/c low water levels. b/c #droughtWhat's worse, many ships on the Rhine transport coals to power plants, as both hydro and nuclear power are on life support. So now, coal power is short, too. 7/

Supply crunches: this affects coal power plants, and your local Walmart/Aldi/Carrefour. Barge traffic is cheap and efficient on the Rhine, Danube and Yangtze, only when there is enough water to float the boats. 6/
On the question, "Why can't they get more power supply from their neighbors?" It's another can of worms we'd be opening and the thread may never end. So more on this later. 5/

b/c they are not supposed to run full-on in times of high heat. What's worse, about half of the reactors are already offline for corrosion and maintenance problems. France's power supply is ~80% nuclear. 4/

This is why, in summer, the usual peak season for hydro power, China's Sichuan province (power supply ~80% hydro), imposed an industrial blackout and residential grey- and yellow-out. And France had to give waivers to nuclear plants to keep running 4/

Blackouts: hydro power plants obv. need water, nuclear power plants need water for cooling (that's why they are almost always built along rivers or coast lines), coal power plants need water for steam generation. But with #drought, no water comes by 3/

Headlines: "worst drought in X number of years" (more on this later), with X>100. Images of people cooling in fountains, or driving motorcycles across part of the Yangtze River, etc..Reality: blackouts, supply crunches, food crisis... 2/
